<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,582,1185]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,726,752]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species was previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[859,1006,726,752]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Abu-Zoherah, R. &amp; Al-Taher, K. &amp; Tilkian, S." box="[1050,1355,726,753]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref29552" refString="Abu-Zoherah, R., Al-Taher, K. &amp; Tilkian, S. (1993) List of Insects Recorded from Saudi Arabia. Ministry of Agriculture and Water, National Agriculture and Water Research Centre, Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, Riyadh, 394 pp." type="book" year="1993">
Abu-Zoherah 
<emphasis box="[1210,1261,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al</emphasis>
. (1993)
</bibRefCitation>
. It was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[327,388,762,788]" name="India" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">India</collectingCountry>
. In terms of Middle Eastern material, there is a specimen labelled “Middle East, 1941-2, J.W. Macfie” and identified by F.I. van Emden. The scanty data is not surprising, since there was a war going on and the collector may have forgotten in the turmoil where he collected it. Prior to this J.W. Macfie was a medical doctor in 
<collectingCountry box="[182,266,870,896]" name="Nigeria" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
who collected insects of medical importance, mainly mosquitoes. There is also a specimen from Port Said, 15.vi.23, R. Loveridge and a further three specimens labelled “Qater Al Khor, Purple Island, 
<date box="[1276,1397,906,933]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="2014-04-25">25.iv.2014</date>
, D. Whitmore.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,582,1185]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,445,978,1004]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
This specimen lacks a posterior bristle on the fore tibia. The adults of species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1796" box="[197,258,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Lispe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[197,258,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Lispe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display morphological variation in populations. It is a fly with a grey abdomen bearing black spots and a silvery grey face.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,582,1185]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,1086,1112]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Biological remarks.</emphasis>
The predaceous larvae live in moist sand and mud alongside water.Adults prey upon other insects and arthropods, both adult and immature (
<bibRefCitation author="Gregor, F. &amp; Rozkosny, R. &amp; Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J." box="[708,920,1122,1148]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="1 - 280" refId="ref32614" refString="Gregor, F., Rozkosny, R., Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J. (2002) The Muscidae (Diptera) of Central Europe. Folia Facultatis Scientiarum Naturalium, Universitatis Masarykianae Brunensis, Biologia, 107, 1 - 280." type="journal article" year="2002">
Gregor 
<emphasis box="[797,854,1122,1148]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al.</emphasis>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Deeming, J. C." box="[932,1103,1122,1148]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref31673" refString="Deeming, J. C. (2008) Order Diptera, family Muscidae. In: van Harten, A. (Ed.), Arthropod Fauna of the United Arab Emirates. Vol. 1. Dar Al-Ummah Printing, Publishing, Distribution &amp; Advertising, Abu Dhabi, pp. 714 - 723." type="book" year="2008">Deeming 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Adults are more likely to be found running on mud.
</paragraph>
